\section*{Sampling units} 

If we assume that it is appropriate to divide the translocation site into 5 x 5 m grid cells and we remove the cells identified by Kate Simister that represent non-habitat (i.e. a 15--20 m strip of thick vegetation in the middle of the area that is intended to slow the dispersal of animals) then we have 46 occupancy units (Figure \ref{units}). As the site is long and thin in order to maximise the number of cells created by gridding up the area of interest I retained any cells which $>$ 23 m\textsuperscript{2} in area.


\section*{Number of surveys} 

The number of surveys required to optimise detection probability was simulated in program R via the "unmarked" package through the construction of matrices based on a detection probability of 0.55 (corresponding to 3 pitfall traps per sampling unit), 46 sampling units, and an occupancy rate of 0.30 (assuming background occupancy will be low but not entirely absent), and 1,000 iterations. The resultant distributions show that improvement in estimation of detection probability attenuates in a diminishing fashion, with little improvement beyond 5 surveys per monitoring session (Figure \ref{survey3pit}).






